6. in hac parte: i.e. in Italy. Cicero's reference to a retreat from Italy on the part of the Pompeians is in the nature of a prophecy. In so far as official in- formation had been given out, a stand was to be made at Luceria. Strangely enough, however, only the day before this letter was written Pompey had ordered his forces to collect at Brundisium with a view to crossing to Dyrra- chium (cf. Att. 8. 12 A. 3), but Cicero did not know this.—-in Cinnae dominatione τ when Ma- rius and Cinna in 87 B.C. ap- proached Rome, many of the Optimates fied, as the same class of men did on the approach of Caesar, but Philippus, Flaccus, and Mucius remained in the city, and Mucius (Q.
